Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] agency (ISI) has been heavily involved in India, with one of the subsections of its Joint Intelligence Bureau department completely devoted to operations against India.<ref name="FAS">{{cite web | url = http://www.fas.org/irp/world/pakistan/isi/ | title = Directorate for Inter-Services Intelligence  | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]] | author = Pike, John | date = 25 July 2002 | accessdate= 25 June 2012 | authorlink = John E. Pike }}</ref> The Joint Signal Intelligence Bureau department has been also supporting [[Kashmir|Kashmiri]] militants in regards to communication.<ref name="FAS"/> The Joint Intelligence North section of the Joint Counter-Intelligence Bureau wing deals exclusively with India.<ref name="Daily">{{cite web | url = http://www.fas.org/irp/world/pakistan/isi/india.html | title = Daily Describes Activities of ISI in India |work=[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]] | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]] | date = 30 June 1999 | accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref> In the 1950s the ISI's Covert Action Division supplied arms to [[Insurgency in Northeast India|insurgents]] in [[Northeast India]].<ref name="FAS"/><ref name="South Asia Analysis Group >{{cite web|url=http://www.acsa.net/isi/index.html|title=PAKISTAN'S INTER-SERVICES INTELLIGENCE (ISI)| accessdate= 25 June 2012|first=B|last=Raman}}</ref> India has also accused the ISI of reinvigorating terrorism in the country via support to the pro-Khalistan militant groups such as [[International Sikh Youth Federation]], in order to take revenge against India for its help in liberation of [[Bangladesh]] as well as to destabilize the Indian State.<ref name=SATPISYF>{{cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/countries/india/states/punjab/terrorist_outfits/ISYF.htm|title=International Sikh Youth Federation (ISYF) South Asia Terrorism Portal article|publisher=The Institute for Conflict Management | accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Shah1997">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=7czT4fipTyoC&dq|author=Mehtab Ali Shah|title=The foreign policy of Pakistan: ethnic impacts on diplomacy, 1971-1994|year=1997|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-86064-169-5|pages=149<U+2013>}}</ref> A report by India's [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] indicated that ISI was "desperately trying to revive Sikh" militant activity in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2008/jun/10vicky.htm|title=200 Pak organisations raise funds for terror: IB|last=Nanjappa|first=Vicky|date=10 June 2008|publisher=Rediff.com|language=Englilsh| accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref> The ISI is also active in printing and supplying [[Counterfeit money|counterfeit]] [[Indian rupee]] notes.<ref name="Chitkara2003">{{cite book|author=M. G. Chitkara|title=Combating Terrorism|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3A0DG8caV6AC&pg=PA296|accessdate=25 June 2012|date=1 January 2003|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-7648-415-2|page=296}}</ref>

==History==
The ISI was created after the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]], due to [[Military Intelligence of Pakistan]]'s weak performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/intell/world/pakistan/isi.htm|title=Directorate for Inter-Services Intelligence |accessdate=28 June 2012|publisher=[[GlobalSecurity.org]]}}</ref> When [[General Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]] [[Operation Fair Play|seized the power]] in July 1977, he started his K2 (Kashmir and Khalistan) strategy, initiating the [[Operation Tupac]].<ref name=ghosh3>Ghosh 2000 pg.3</ref> He gave ISI the duty to make Jammu and Kashmir a part of Pakistan, and to send the terrorists to Punjab.<ref name=ghosh3/> According to arrested ISI agents, the intelligence agency's aims are to confound [[Indian Muslims]] using [[Kashmiri Muslims]]; to extend the network of the ISI; to grow the framework of terrorists; to initiate [[1993 Bombay bombings]] like attack in other cities, and to cause a state of insurgency in Muslim dominated regions.<ref name=ghosh8>Ghosh 2000 pg.8</ref> The ISI had set up bases in Nepal and Bangladesh, which are used for operations in North-East India.<ref name=ghosh8/>

==Operations in Jammu and Kashmir==
About [[Pakistani rupee|Rs.]] 2.4 [[crore]] are paid out per month by the ISI, in order to fund its activities in [[Jammu and Kashmir]].<ref name="FAS"/> Pro-Pakistani groups were reportedly favored over other militant groups.<ref name=FAS/> Creation of six militant groups in Kashmir, which included [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT), was aided by the ISI.<ref name=Salon>[http://www.salon.com/opinion/feature/2008/12/12/pakistan/index.html Does Obama understand his biggest foreign-policy challenge?], [[Salon.com]], 2008-12-12</ref><ref name=NYT1>[http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/01/world/asia/01pstan.html Pakistani Militants Admit Role in Siege, Official Says], [[The New York Times]], 2009-01-01</ref> According to American Intelligence officials, ISI is still providing protection and help to LeT.<ref name=NYT1/> The [[Pakistan Army]] and ISI also LeT volunteers to surreptitiously penetrate from [[Pakistan Administrated Kashmir]] to Jammu and Kashmir.<ref name="tellis2010">{{Cite news| title = Bad Company <U+2013> Lashkar-e-Tayyiba and the Growing Ambition of Islamist Militancy in Pakistan| url = http://www.internationalrelations.house.gov/111/tel031110.pdf| format = PDF| date = 11 March 2010| author = Ashley J. Tellis| publisher = Carnegie Endowment for International Peace}}</ref> As of 2010, the degree of control that ISI retains over LeT<U+2019>s operations is not known.<ref name='lisacurtis2010'>{{Cite document | first = Lisa | last = Curtis | contribution = Bad Company: Lashkar-e-Tayyiba and the Growing Ambition of Islamist Militancy in Pakistan | title = Testimony to US Congress Committee on Foreign Affairs | place = Washington, DC | date = 2010-03-11}}</ref> The LeT was also reported to have been directed by the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) to widen its network in the Jammu region where a considerable section of the populace comprised Punjabis.<ref>[http://www.eyespymag.com/terrorgroupsL-M.htm Lashkar-e-Taiba],''Eyespymag''</ref>

==Involvement in terrorist attacks==
===Involvement with 26/11 attacks===
[[Zabiuddin Ansari]], a Lashkar-e-Taiba militant accused for his involvement in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]], said that ISI and [[Pakistani army]] officials were involved in planning the attacks and had attended the meetings.<ref name=TOI_Saudi_help>{{cite news|title=Saudis helped India nab 26/11 handler Abu Jundal|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Saudis-helped-India-nab-26/11-handler-Abu-Jundal/articleshow/14396009.cms|accessdate=25 June 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 June 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/68hCOOW5G|archivedate=2012-06-25|}}</ref> An Indian report, summarising intelligence gained from India's interrogation of [[David Headley]],<ref name="ap-20101019">{{Cite news|url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101019/ap_on_re_as/as_india_mumbai_attack|title=Indian gov't: Pakistan spies tied to Mumbai siege|work=news.yahoo.com|agency=Associated Press|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=20 October 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101021114840/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101019/ap_on_re_as/as_india_mumbai_attack| archivedate= 21 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> alleged that ISI had provided support for the attacks by providing funding for reconnaissance missions in Mumbai.<ref name="fox-20101019">{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/10/19/indian-report-pakistan-spies-tied-mumbai-siege/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+foxnews%2Fworld+%28Internal+-+World+Latest+-+Text%29|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=20 October 2010|title=Report: Pakistan Spies Tied to Mumbai Siege|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101122010702/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/10/19/indian-report-pakistan-spies-tied-mumbai-siege/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+foxnews%2Fworld+%28Internal+-+World+Latest+-+Text%29| archivedate= 22 November 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The report included Headley's claim that Lashkar-e-Taiba's chief military commander, [[Zaki-ur-Rahman Lakhvi]], had close ties to the ISI.<ref name="ap-20101019">{{Cite news|url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101019/ap_on_re_as/as_india_mumbai_attack|title=Indian gov't: Pakistan spies tied to Mumbai siege|work=news.yahoo.com|agency=Associated Press|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=20 October 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101021114840/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101019/ap_on_re_as/as_india_mumbai_attack| archivedate= 21 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> He alleged that "every big action of LeT is done in close coordination with [the] ISI."<ref name="fox-20101019"/>

===Involvement with Mumbai train blasts===
ISI was alleged of planning the [[2006 Mumbai train bombings]]. The Indian government said that the ISI, LeT and [[Students Islamic Movement of India|SIMI]] planned the attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/asiapcf/09/30/india.bombs/index.html?section=cnn_world#|title=Pakistan spy agency behind Mumbai bombings|author=CNN|date=30 September 2006|accessdate=30 September 2006|publisher=CNN}}</ref>

==Counterfeit Indian rupee notes==
The ISI has been alleged to print counterfeit Indian rupee notes, which are believed to be printed in [[Muzaffarabad]], in order to ruin Indian economy.<ref name=ghosh101>Ghosh 2000 pg.101</ref> In January 2000, the Nepal police raided Wasim Saboor's house, who was an official of the [[List of diplomatic missions of Pakistan|Pakistani embassy]] of [[Kathmandu]].<ref name=ghosh102>Ghosh 2000 pg.102</ref> They found fifty thousand Indian rupee notes, each of Rs.50 denomination.<ref name=ghosh102/>

